text:
we are seen too strong to show when we are weak.
beaten and battered we are blamed for our own demise. seen for our magic but not our humanity. 
seen only for our magic and never for our humanity
expected to save the world with the power they keep taking. our bodies expected scapegoats for the world to place its sin on. black femme i pray for us. no more can we go on this way. a moment of rage for all us who are falling and have fallen before us. may they see the humanity that makes us magic. that personhood gives us power. we are not their hero. the time is now for our salvation from the hands that we have saved. 
#blackfemmepoet #blackpoet #blackfemmesmatter #blackgirlsmatter #metoo #blackgirlhuman #thefutureisblackandfemme #notyourblacksuperhero #blackfemmesofinstagram

text:
#metoo
when i found the courage and strength to come forward and go public about the sexual abuse, sexual harassment and discrimination i endured at my job at the university of illinois chicago with ceasefire- cure violence, i knew it would be hard. i knew that the closer i get to exposing these monsters the harder they would hit back. 
i have now become a victim of a hoax to attempt to assassinate my character. which of course means that these people are desperate.
the truth will always prevail.
i stand by my words, i stand by my claims, i stand in alliance with the other women who were abused by this man. i will not go away!
i stand strong!
i will not back down or be broken.
i am extremely grateful for my legal team and everyone who supports me. thank you, bianca 
#uic #sph #enoughisenough #ceasefire #cureviolence #stopsexabusers

- his ex-wife spoke out on their marriage being physically and mentally abusive for 13 years, as well as being a deadbeat dad - jovante cunningham, a former backup dancer, claims she saw him having sex with a minor in the studio with an audience
- lizzette martinez was one of the minors kelly was sexually involved with, who got pregnant with his baby and later miscarried; she was the inspiration for hit song you are not alone (written for michael jackson)
- began a sexual relationship with tiffany hawkins, 15, when he was 24
- married singer, aaliyah, 15, when he was 27 by forging papers to say she was 18 [see slide 5]; marriage was later annulled by her mother
- a video of kelly engaging in sexual activity, and urinating on a minor later surfaced
- the same year as the video, he was indicted on 21 counts of child pornography
- he created an abusive sex cult, where women could not leave his house
- knowingly gave his partner an std

they are the ones who build this society. 
moms, wives, sisters, daughters,
everyone. 
don't judge them by their clothes. by their hair. the colour they wear. 
buddy if it wasn't of them. 
you won't even exist. 
it's funny how in most species the female is considered the stronger one. 
and then there's us. humans. 
we as men should not judge.
also this doesn't mean women can do whatever they want on the basis of feminism and women empowerment. 
we all should go hand in hand. regardless of all our differences of caste, colour, religion, gender, nationality.
we are humans. 
so let's show some humanity.
united!

text:
and this is a prime example of how in-group social stratification affects the visibility of the victimized
.

both neal degrasse tyson and rkelly have been accused by *black woman* of harrasment. for kelly, this dates back to the early 90s, for degrasse tyson only a few years. we've seen a rapid fire response to degrasse and nearly no movement at all for kelly. that's not a mere coincidence, it's locked in the ugly and largely hidden reality of social stratification
.

why? in the economic landscape of american cultural currancy, neal degrasse tyson is more "valuable" then kelly, which trickles down to his victims; degrasse "abuses" "good" black woman, kelly abuses "bad" black woman, notions of disposablity being *the* driving element behind american sex trade ...which hasn't budged even a dollar since the #metoo and white ladies movement began. why? this category of victim-disposablity renders her or *him* completely invisible
.

based on the *perception* of *value*, we saw an entirely different process of base investigation unfold on behalf of their victims. .

how is this value assessed? education, not cash. rkelly was both rich and hyper-visible when he was actively raping black children. degrasse tyson has a blurry interaction with a peer, dating back to college. worth, as it applies to human currancy, is based *first* on education. it's the dividing line of precived value of the black american via the lens of white america
.

now, this is *completely nonsensical*. to assert that a black child from the inner city has fewer social rights then a college age black female student, as they apply to sexual abuse, is *absurd*, but it's the fundamental reason the woman's movement was devoid of inner city black women. if you saw a black woman involved in the white ladies movement? she was from the upper-middle class
.

our communities refusal to engage in (possibly painful) discussions about the scope of american economics will only continue this bizarre psychology
.

to work to change this, in-group across class dialogue is *essential* to dismantle something as alarming as this long-held, fixed value system. if we don't do it? statistics won't budge

an overnight journey in a train, a visit to a crowded market, a bus journey to the office. such populated public places ought to be very safe right?  wrong. the untold stories of countless women who face sexual harassment in public spaces is shocking. even worse, sexual harassment in a public spaces is not a codified offence recognised by law. 
introducing reachout‚Äôs collaboration with @womenthroughthelens , a movement dedicated to lending a voice to women who have been ignored for far too long. as implementing partners, we plan to prepare a manual to spread awareness in government schools, sensitise police officers and a lot more.

text:
in october i was violently sexually assaulted by a coward in a club smoking area, that night i walked around with my tights ripped by his hands trying to drink and laugh myself out of the dull headache his hair pulling caused me. 
i was told to not let him ruin my night but not only did he ruin my night in the months following it felt like he ruined my life.
i could see his face every time i lied in bed and what hurt the most i can physically see his face on the clubs instagram tag. i can see his smiling face posing with friends in the same area he destroyed my confidence and my sense of safety.

for months after i lied in scolding baths everyday for hours on end to feel clean, i cut off the hair he touched i bagged and hid the clothing he destroyed. 
i had to answer police questions alone, i had to cry at night alone. because i refused to speak up and tell those around me i felt like i was dying every-time someone touched me from behind without warning. 
but this year i won‚Äôt sit down quietly and act ashamed because why should i feel shameful when the actions that should make stomachs turn weren‚Äôt my own?

i‚Äôm not broken and i‚Äôm not unclean i possess more strength in the tip of my finger than the man who did this has in his entire body. 
i know this now i‚Äôm self aware to the strength and resilience i possess.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

i was told to not let him ruin my night but not only did he ruin my night in the months following it felt like he ruined my life.
i could see his face every time i lied in bed and what hurt the most i can physically see his face on the clubs instagram tag. i can see his smiling face posing with friends in the same area he destroyed my confidence and my sense of safety.

for months after i lied in scolding baths everyday for hours on end to feel clean, i cut off the hair he touched i bagged and hid the clothing he destroyed. 
i had to answer police questions alone, i had to cry at night alone. because i refused to speak up and tell those around me i felt like i was dying every-time someone touched me from behind without warning. 
but this year i won‚Äôt sit down quietly and act ashamed because why should i feel shameful when the actions that should make stomachs turn weren‚Äôt my own?

i‚Äôm not broken and i‚Äôm not unclean i possess more strength in the tip of my finger than the man who did this has in his entire body. 
i know this now i‚Äôm self aware to the strength and resilience i possess.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
#metoo #metoomovement #feminist #nonbinary #queer #lgbt #art #femme #femmefatale #bisexual

text:
understanding the cycle of abuse .

ongoing abuse is cyclical. it becomes a self-defeating mechanism whereby the abuser gains power and control over the victim, manipulating that person into thinking that they cannot change what is happening, and in fact may be destined to suffer.

at first, the victim is charmed by the kindness of the individual and feels love for that person. protection is granted and accepted, as well as the provision of companionship and love. as time goes on, however, the protection turns into restrictive control of resources and social activities. the victim is not allowed certain privileges or amenities and contact with the outside world is limited.

the abuser becomes angry or uses physical harm, forcing the victim to keep in line with unrealistic expectations and demands. any time there is an infraction, it is grounds for punishment, demeaning comments, and accusations. the victim is humiliated and made to feel they are at fault, and the action against them is warranted due to the nature of the wrongdoing.

once the abusive incident has passed, it is as if it never happened. no mention is made of the incident and the victim is treated with love and gratitude. there is an outpouring of kindness and gentleness, to the point that the victim‚Äôs feelings of love for the abuser are reinforced, and they think that the incident was isolated and probably will not happen again.
.
.
.

text:
took a huge step this week... told my sister about what happened to me. she was/continues to be really supportive. i‚Äôve been basically feeling one of these since then... 1) utter shock, the world didn‚Äôt end. nothing is different. nothing is happening. some thoughts like, this is what i‚Äôve been afraid of? why didn‚Äôt i do this a long time ago or when i was a child? maybe a little guilt or judgment that i didn‚Äôt disclose earlier. not sure yet, have a lot to still process. but i know that the last thought isn‚Äôt helpful, so trying not to get stuck in it. 2.) frenetic energy, uncomfortable, not sure how i feel, uncontained. this is what i associate with my ‚Äúvulnerability hangovers‚Äù whenever i talk about my trauma. this is what i‚Äôm afraid of feeling and try to avoid. 3.) start focusing on food, but i‚Äôve actually done a decent job of not using it as an excuse to restrict. except if i‚Äôm being honest, my plan is to restrict today. ü§¶üèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è but my hubby is making breakfast right now, so that will be helpfui. ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äîi have a feeling that the next few months will be really rough and a lot of feeling number 2. but i think a part of this work is almost building a tolerance for feeling so bad and not acting on any self destructive urges, so that you actually feel what you‚Äôre feeling. easier said than done for sure. ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
the plan in the next few emdr sessions is that i talk in detail about everything that has happened. i know we can certainly go at my own pace, but it is different going into a therapy session with the intention of talking about trauma stuff. i‚Äôm actually feeling a little better after writing all this. lots of love to anyone struggling üíó

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
it took me a couple years after leaving the relationship to realize how strong i am.  after leaving i faced a pregnancy with no emotional support.  all i really heard was "you screwed up again" "i wish i could go back and stay so this wouldn't have happened" "this is now your life of struggle" and that all came from my family. 
the day i told my sister i was pregnant, she went to my neighbor, whom i didn't really know besides she was a mom around the same age as me, married with 2 kids and a pretty normal life, and told her literally the entire bad side of my situation.  aired all my dirty laundry to someone i had just met...my sisters reasoning was "mom didn't answer her phone"
i was humiliated. 
it took a lot for me to start building2rebuild, it took courage that i had to find myself and strength that i didn't know i had.  it hasn't been easy and my sister actually threatened me with a lawsuit a couple months ago but i decided a year ago i was not going to become a product of my situation and i will continue to work and make strides everyday to a happy and healthy future for my boys. 
i will tell my story, the one that so many have tried to viciously tell for me.  i will give strength to others with my words and hope with my truth.  no one can back me into a corner again and i am sure of that!

text:
black backs bending backwards only to be broken.
suffocating on the very essence of life i‚Äôm choking.
and ain‚Äôt i a woman, don‚Äôt hashtag me.
stand up when they push me down, parallel to the ground. beat me blue like black don‚Äôt bruise, black bruises adorn her eye. seems as colored tears are america‚Äôs favorite lullaby.
lulling them to sleep, because the louder we scream the quieter the speak.
and i ain‚Äôt i a woman? 
worth protecting, who gave you life?
but you‚Äôd take mine without thinking twice.
i know the cost of living ain‚Äôt free, but ain‚Äôt i paid the price?

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
ever since #sexual #assault allegations against #hollywood producer harvey weinstein came to light last year, the #metoo movement ‚Äî initially launched over a decade ago by activist tarana burke ‚Äî has prompted millions of #survivors around the world to come forward and share their own stories. moreover, after #actress alyssa milano's #metoo tweet went viral in october 2017, #metoo has caused #google searches about sexual assault to shatter records and reach an all-time high.
.
.
last october, #the newyork times broke the news that #weinstein had faced numerous sexual assault allegations over the years, and that he had paid off his accusers. since then, numerous prominent figures ‚Äî from actors and comedians to lawmakers and scientists ‚Äî have been held accountable for sexual #violence and #abuse, and the #metoo movement has sparked increased awareness about these issues.
.
.
following the weinstein scandal, researchers from #harvard medical school and uc #sandiego took a look at google #search rates for sexual harassment and sexual assault before and after milano's #metoo tweet. to start, the researchers examined trends in these searches from jan. 1, 2004 to oct. 14, 2017 ‚Äî the day before milano first tweeted about #metoo..
.
.
they then used this data to roughly estimate how many times americans would search for these subjects following her tweet, and found that searches for sexual harassment and assault were 86 percent higher than expected from oct. 15, 2017 to june 15, 2018. researchers also discovered a 51 percent increase in searches about preventive training for sexual #harassment and assault, and a 30 percent increase in searches about reporting cases of sexual violence.

according to the #chicago tribune, burke first coined the phrase "me too" in 2006, in order to support women ‚Äî especially black women and women of color ‚Äî who had survived sexual violence. burke has continuously worked to combat sexual violence... read more:

https://www.bustle.com/p/google-searches-about-sexual-assault-harassment-broke-a-record-after-metoo-researchers-say-15561117

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
'feminism is the radical notion that women are human beings.' - marie shear.
-----
i picked this card up years ago at the national portrait gallery. that was way before the #metoo #timesup and #yesallwomen movement, and it really hit home. i think that was also the first time i had an inkling of what i really wanted to write about. i had no idea about what genre i was going to write in or what even my story was in the broadest sense of the word, but i knew i wanted to write about what it means to be seen as less of a person and more of an object because you've got boob. there's been a lot of talk about sexual harassment in public places, i.e.: from work colleagues and what constitutes as  overstepping the boundaries and so on. but sometimes those boundaries aren't necessarily very clear, for example when the abuse happens behind closed doors in a relationship. before i even moved to the uk, i did a course in domestic violence at a university in the us, and the most difficult area to police is emotional abuse in relationships because most of the time the victim doesn't even realize what is happening to them, and generally blames themselves for the abuse they receive. i've been introduced to a whole new world filled with words such as gaslighting, narcissistic behaviour, cognitive dissonance, divide and conquer and enablers. the list goes on. 
and when i read 'if women rose rooted' by sharon blackie (@sharonblackiemythmakings) and her article on the dangerous woman project, i knew i had my story setting. despite not having a drop of irish blood in me, the story of celtic warrior women who had been written out of history by christian monks really hit home. 
so here i am several years later, trying to do her story justice. .
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
the night i learned ‚Äúyou‚Äôre beautiful‚Äù sometimes means ‚Äúi own you.‚Äù
.
.
my beauty caused pain 
on a night when it rained
to the bar, a man came
with his turkish friend james
now in comes the sorrow
i got up, he followed
so scared that i swallowed
but courage i borrowed
from all of the women
from here to new zealand
who know this same feeling
the shame i‚Äôm re-living 
pinned me to the wall
my fist up, i balled
swift sock to the jaw
and kick to the balls
when women say no
it doesn‚Äôt mean go
or to take it slow
i‚Äôm letting you know
to all of the ‚Äúgents‚Äù
with aggressive intent
go fall in a ditch
you sick piece of shit üôÉ

alexasym

.
.

i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
i sit here under the trees. i am drawn to their safe shade. sheltered from the fast approaching midday sun. 
there‚Äôs a breeze that‚Äôs very fond of caressing my hair. 
i roll out my yoga mat and stretch out a bit. i feel heavy emotions. it seems like my husband and i keep going through these waves of utter bliss and utter discomfort with one another. today is the latter. 
i remember my taoist training. ancient chinese energy medicine of letting the trees alchemize all unwanted energies to include sickness. i speak to the trees as i feel their energy field saying hello. i greet them back recognizing their kindness in hosting me. i immediately feel a rush of energy run over me. as if i‚Äôm warmly being hugged. ‚Äúdraw closer dear child. we are here for you. breathe and rest onto us.‚Äú the sound of the call to prayer echos in the distance and suddenly i am flooded with memories of my childhood. of the parks my parents  would take me to. of how beautiful and cherished those memories were and yet i remember not being able to fully be myself. there was a burden i was carrying as a little girl. my father had made me put on a headscarf to fend away any unwanted male attention that came towards the 9 year old me. apparently i was told quite a lot that i looked russian, something that i later would find out was culturally referenced as synonymous with being a prostitute in 1990s bahrain. i was half italian after all. with my porcelain skin and dark hair, rosy cheeks and plump rosy lips; i thought i looked more like snow white than a ‚Äúrussian‚Äù. i had no idea what that even meant. all i knew it was bad and it brought in grown men‚Äôs attention and weird energy that i didn‚Äôt like and that‚Äôs why i had to cover up. the way men reacted to me made me feel weird. and unsafe. and it was somehow very wrong. 
and i was told it was my fault.  that grown men would stare at a child. would gawk. would sexually harass a child. would flash a child. somehow. it was my fault. i remember these being my first sexual memories after that time i was molested by the family driver when i was about 5... continued ‚¨áÔ∏è

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

in the first nordic model now! podcast, anna talks with trixie from nordic model now! about being groomed into prostitution when she was a teenager in 1989 and her life being pimped on the streets of leeds in the north of england for the next 11 years.

her story shows the insidious nature of the grooming process, and the increasing use of violence and coercive control by her pimp, who was also her partner and the father to her three children. anna speaks about the punters who paid for sex, the other women she was prostituted with, the connections with the local lap dancing club, and the long-term effects ‚Äòthe life‚Äô has had on herself and her children.  her story is harrowing and contains descriptions of violence and abuse that you may find disturbing.

her story shows the insidious nature of the grooming process, and the increasing use of violence and coercive control by her pimp, who was also her partner and the father to her three children. anna speaks about the punters who paid for sex, the other women she was prostituted with, the connections with the local lap dancing club, and the long-term effects ‚Äòthe life‚Äô has had on herself and her children.  her story is harrowing and contains descriptions of violence and abuse that you may find disturbing.

we‚Äôve been restricted in cages,
for time immemorial since ages,
we‚Äôve succumbed all our lives,
in your world of despise.

are you not impure?
after all you were born out of coarse,
or purity is limited to your gender?
and we are buried under your auspices of smirch,
at your disposal to be plundered.

which deity discriminates?
if there was any, ever,
you think yourself our tutelage,
while you are merely a dodgy fraud,
submerged in your act of pillage.

you think you can restrain us,
with your deception of purification,
when you failed to purify your mind and soul,
and thought to withhold,
what was never yours.

whichever ritual you perform,
you‚Äôll remain dependent on us,
for your generation wont progress,
in absence of uterus.

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong

text: these will always be 4 words that drive me bonkers in terms of leaving toxic and abusive relationships. i finally sat and watched #survivingrkelly and i kept hearing this question in my head and from others who felt that it was somehow impossible to be abused. i can recall my own story of after i left an abusive relationship at age 29 and it didn't matter who i told everybody asked me "what did you do?" as though the series of events that led to the abuse could go either way (my fault or his). that is exactly how these women's stories are being looked at as though people are asking "what did you do." its not a matter of what they did or didn't do it's a matter of being taken advantage of and being abused mentally, emotionally, physically and sexually. regardless of age, length of time with the abuser or anything. abusers know how to manipulate everyone around them (they didnt just get these girls by actually kidnapping them) they got in good with the parents, acted like prince charming in public, treated the girls like princesses all the while slowly manipulating and controlling them which is why when the real severe abuse started they were already broken and feared leaving. i stayed with my abuser for 2.5 years. i made excuses for his behavior, i neglected my family, i was ashamed, embarrassed, broken and felt that i couldn't go back to my family. abusers make sure they control your every move and they always hang something over your head that keeps you stuck with them for fear of exposure. so stop asking "what did you do" and ask "how can i help" or "are you doing ok." abuse survivors went through hell with their abuser and they damn sure don't want to go through hell with their family and friends. surviving r-kelly shed some serious light on r-kelly, the families, their daughters and how his abuse has affected all of them. #survivor #abuseisnotok #speakup #youarenotalone #metoo #timesup #talentdoesnotnegateabuse #listen #abuseisabuse #bringthosegirlshome #abuseisnotlove

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
today, i apologize to myself for discrediting her throughout the years. today, i celebrate my goddess energy. 
in the past, i've allowed society to instill fear in me. fear of my voice. fear of my power. fear of my mind. fear of my own body! i was a co-creator of my own worries... an enabler of injustice against the feminine. i had forgotten that society cannot devalue us without our permission.

i also forgot that no one can hurt or destroy a goddess, as she is the creator, destroyer, and lover. 
today, and everyday i choose to reclaim my power and rightful place as a goddess and descendant of powerful women. 
in these pictures, ancient egyptian goddess sekhmet embodies many roles. she's depicted with the face of a lionness. initially, she was created to punish mankind... an unstoppable force of energy and karma. at risk of destroying mankind, she eventually evolved into hathor (2nd photo), the goddess of joy, love, and fertility. 
sekhmet is so fierce and versatile, that she can be one's punishment or joy, depending on the circumstance. she's also the protector of maat, the goddess of justice, truth, and destiny. 'she' is everything. 'she' embodies freedom. 'she' is powerful. 'she' has purpose. 'she' is love. 'she' is destiny.

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text: i‚Äôm female, i know how it feels to be subjected to play the role of kitchen-stayer or be seen as just a child-bearer, i strongly believe that whatever a man can do, i can (also) do; but i will sincerely acknowledge that i mean this when it comes to intellectuality and not physical strength. if we want gender equality because we want to eradicate the school of thought some people have that women are not supposed to be part of decision making, that they should not be allowed to even go outside, drive cars or let alone play important roles in the government, that all we should do is sit, cook, satisfy sexually, breed and look pretty and do as we are told, then i‚Äôm all for gender equality. my religion (christianity) tells me to be submissive to my husband, and my husband is supposed to protect me. i will obey this if i want to. and it will be crazy for my society to tell me to live in subjugation because i am a woman; i am equally as intelligent (if not more intelligent) than a man. if a nation wants to grow, they have to be willing to know that women can even be more productive than men, they have to accept us as equals, not look down on us as lesser beings. in my opinion, men should do the manly stuff and women do the womanly stuff; because we want to, because it‚Äôs what we‚Äôre supposed to do, not because society forces us to. and women have the right to be presidents; likewise, men have the right to be stay-at-home dads.... #feminism #feminist #equality #womenempowerment #gender #humanrights #girlpower #womensrights #intersectionalfeminism #equalrights #lgbt #women #transgender #gay #lgbtq #metoo #transgender #activist #art #genderfluid #nonbinary #girls #education #bisexual #girl #empowerment #strongwomen #gendermainstreaming #gay

text:
streaming has changed films for better: sandra bullock

actress sandra bullock, who stars in netflix's acclaimed thriller "bird box", believes that "streaming has elevated the bar" in terms of opportunities for actors. "cinema is not going anywhere, streaming has elevated the bar. before, if you were a superhero, you were able to get a movie made; anything else was not getting made. now, with streaming, we have all kinds of work available," bullock told the i paper. 
she added: "the movie business is changing, and providing so many more opportunities for women and for people of colour." the "ocean's 8" star went on to explain that she feels the industry is changing in all ways and said she saw a notable difference in attitudes towards women before and after filming the all-female heist flick, reports femalefirst.co.uk. 
she said: "we started that film before #metoo and we ended it during. i saw a noticeable difference." despite changing attitudes, the "proposal" actress also noticed a difference while filming "bird box" due to the presence of a female director, susanne bier. 
the spine-chilling drama follows a pregnant woman in a dystopian future, where people are forced to wear blindfolds to avoid witnessing their biggest fears.

.
.
i grew up wondering if i‚Äôd ever have my innocence back or if i‚Äôd ever enjoy sex the way it‚Äôs intended! no one in my life knows about this and i know it will cause many questions and speculations and i don‚Äôt apologize for who it might offend because to be honest, i have been dealing with the aftermath of trauma with every person i‚Äôve encountered in an intimate way after the abuse‚Äîbecause it never goes away!
.
.

text:
microphone check, check 1..2..3... i am on my soap box today.  i absolutely love to talk about relationships as you know!  however, i enjoy seeing people happy, families and married couples.  just keeping it realllllllll!!! however, when it comes to relationships there is 1 thing i see very wrong.  #####mute....####metoo you know exactly where i am going with this.  this is what i am talking about here, these darn messed up unhealthy relationships we have going on in this world here between men and women, teenage girls and older men .....just messed up.  let‚Äôs talk to our baby girls and fill them up with love mothers and daddies come and hold tight to your daughters show them what true love is, show them their worth. 
also, i am disappointed about how so much disrespect has been expressed toward women.  to make things worse i have to express all of this to my daughter who believes that the black woman is the most hated woman in this world and it really hurt my heart to hear her say that.  this is no longer a subject that needs to be ignored any longer.  we can not sit back and keep quiet because of fear, shame or rejection.  it‚Äôs true that more than 30% of women in relationships have experienced some kind of abuse, domestic, rape, sexual harassment in their life from ages 14 and up this has practically become an epidemic.  the worst thing we can do is to continue  to keep quiet or take a payoff to keep quiet to protect the predators.  this is some of the reasoning behind failed relationships starting with yourself, although it goes so much deeper than this.  hurt people hurt people.  first as women we must respect and honor ourselves.  know that we are deserving and worthy of respect to put a stop to what has happened. we have to become our own solution for change to produce healthy loving supportive relationships in our lives. #speakupnow no matter if the relationship is with a coworker, a boss, a minister, a sibling, a parent, a leader or authoritative figure, even a partner know that you don‚Äôt have to be manipulated, intimidated and neither do you have to play small just to feel safe in your position. 
#metoo#muterkelly#speakoutnow#relationshipgoals

text:
black women have culturally been physically and sexually abused and trafficked. we have been objectified, beaten, ‚Äúbitched‚Äù, and betrayed...
the laws of human nature has typically caused us to hone in on the one thing without deeply looking at the whole of how we have failed to protect our girls and lift up our women.
how about beginning with the issue of molestation in own homes first? the legacy of that shit!..it‚Äôs not a lifetime series...it‚Äôs life.
how about looking deeply into the burdens cast upon women that bear the burden of being black (because i don‚Äôt know shit about being brown)?
how about examining the impact on the imagination and the ability to exist in this world after being lifted and left at the same time.
it‚Äôs a whole bunch that are guilty when it comes to the plight of black girls who fight for their birthright to be women.
as a people, we gotta look at the whole and not a single part~ because we are a legacy of slavery that is mental and messed up.

#metoo #molestation #abuse #objectifiedwomen #madatmyles #pearlcleage #spelman #blackwomenconsciousness #domesticviolence #womenforwomensrights #endtrafficking #changeforchildren #protectourgirls

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

#repost from @cleezereport with @regram.app ... last year bette midler renewed allegation geraldo rivera groped her... actor posts video of 1991 interview in which she describes alleged assault, saying tv host and producer pushed drugs ‚Äòunder my nose‚Äô

bette midler renewed an allegation of 1970s sexual misconduct against geraldo rivera on thursday, a day after rivera called the news business ‚Äúflirty‚Äù amid matt lauer‚Äôs dismissal by nbc.

in the tweet posted by the actor-singer and confirmed by her publicist, she included a video from the 1991 interview with barbara walters in which midler made the allegation against rivera. ‚Äútomorrow is my birthday. i feel like this video was a gift from the universe to me. geraldo may have apologized for his tweets supporting matt lauer, but he has yet to apologize for this,‚Äù midler posted, adding the harassment-solidarity hashtag ‚Äú#metoo‚Äù. a representative for rivera did not immediately respond to a request for comment. fox news channel, which currently employs rivera but did not in the 70s, did not immediately comment on midler‚Äôs post.

in the clip, midler hesitates in recounting what she alleges happened with rivera during his visit to interview her in the early 70s, saying it will get her in trouble. ‚Äúget in a little trouble,‚Äù walters encourages her.

after rivera and a producer left their tv crew in another room, they ‚Äúpushed me into my bathroom. they broke two poppers and pushed them under my nose and proceeded to grope me,‚Äù she said. ‚Äúpoppers‚Äù is slang for the alkyl nitrites class of drugs. ‚Äúi did not offer myself up on the altar of geraldo rivera,‚Äù said midler, calling his behavior ‚Äúunseemly‚Äù. after midler tells walters that she had no way of knowing ‚Äúthese things are going to come back to haunt you‚Äù, walters suggests they discuss other subjects.

walters opened up the topic by asking about midler‚Äôs reaction to rivera‚Äôs 1991 autobiography exposing myself, including what walters called his account of a ‚Äútorrid sexual affair‚Äù with midler, whom he labeled ‚Äúinsatiable‚Äù. midler smiles, saying she was glad the book ran counter to her image at the time of the interview as that of a ‚Äúsomewhat strait-laced‚Äù older lady.

text:
two words will forever be attached to robert sylvester kelly's legacy. genius and predator. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
genius, in the sense that you can't deny his talent. his music catalog has created so many memories and painted the r&b and pop music landscape over the length of his career. yet, intertwined in all that god given ability is a man who has systematically preyed on, assaulted, brainwashed and degraded women. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
building off of the bbc's documentary from last year; r kelly: sex, girls & videotapes. lifetime aired a more in-depth six-part series "surviving r. kelly" over the past three days.  presented over the timeline of his life utilizing historical footage, expert interviews and survivors' testimonies, what could have been easily portrayed as a hit piece against r. kelly; executive producer dream hampton and company took great care to make sure that they presented a balanced viewpoint regarding such a controversial figure, but mainly for the women who spoke up to have their voices heard. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
the series traces how kelly with a probable learning disability blossomed as a teenage musical prodigy and eventually became an r&b superstar. yet, what wasn't known to the public at large, until much later was that kelly suffered his own sexual abuse. so, it's very sad that a man who has suffered from this would go and allegedly turn around and do the same thing to women of color. kelly for so long has been able to get away with this monstrous behavior because of the cast of enablers from rca records execs, to those who worked for and with him, radio stations, and finally the listening public by choosing his music over believing the allegations against him over the years. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
still to this day, kelly performs at different venues around the world even with this hanging over his head. for how much longer is a different question to be asked after the airing of this documentary. from beginning to end, the series was riveting, while holding a mirror to the music industry, if not society. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä

text:
here's my full review over @2sensory about "surviving r. kelly"‚†Ä
‚†Ä
two words will forever be attached to robert sylvester kelly's legacy. genius and predator. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
genius, in the sense that you can't deny his talent. his music catalog has created so many memories and painted the r&b and pop music landscape over the length of his career. yet, intertwined in all that god given ability is a man who has systematically preyed on, assaulted, brainwashed and degraded women. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
building off of the bbc's documentary from last year; r kelly: sex, girls & videotapes. lifetime aired a more in-depth six-part series "surviving r. kelly" over the past three days.  presented over the timeline of his life utilizing historical footage, expert interviews and survivors' testimonies, what could have been easily portrayed as a hit piece against r. kelly; executive producer dream hampton and company took great care to make sure that they presented a balanced viewpoint regarding such a controversial figure, but mainly for the women who spoke up to have their voices heard. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
the series traces how kelly with a probable learning disability blossomed as a teenage musical prodigy and eventually became an r&b superstar. yet, what wasn't known to the public at large, until much later was that kelly suffered his own sexual abuse. so, it's very sad that a man who has suffered from this would go and allegedly turn around and do the same thing to women of color. kelly for so long has been able to get away with this monstrous behavior because of the cast of enablers from rca records execs, to those who worked for and with him, radio stations, and finally the listening public by choosing his music over believing the allegations against him over the years. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
still to this day, kelly performs at different venues around the world even with this hanging over his head. for how much longer is a different question to be asked after the airing of this documentary. from beginning to end, the series was riveting, while holding a mirror to the music industry, if not society. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
#survingrkelly #metoo #timesup

we think we have to have the right book, or the right pastor, or the right formula, or the right church, or the right this or that before we can be victorious. dear friend, you already have all the resources you need to live a victorious life. the same life which rose christ up from the dead dwells in you. if the life can do that, what is there that it cannot do in your life?
.
.
do not put your trust in your church. do not put your trust in your pastor. trust in the life of christ to do what you cannot within yourself. if death, hell, and the grave could not hold him back, do not worry that your problems are going to be too much for him to handle.
.
.

text:
#24speciesofcrane day 24

antigone vipio, the white naped crane. 
pictured with a deliciously vegan pavlova as invented by @australia. this is a great alternative christmas puddings for the average #homevegancook due to its simplicity, yet unlike many vegan christmas cake recipes it is delicious, nutritious and healthy too.

discovered in 1811 by the juggernaut of prussian zoological studies, peter simon pallas. pallas is more commonly known for the crater elevation theory that explains the manner in which mountain ranges are created by volcanic eruptions as igneuos rocks are present on mountain peaks, this was obvious to the learned botanist and thus in 1777 he had laid the foundation of the much celebrated #flatearth model. pallas was a pioneer of reputational overreach, applying the the strong scientific resume of a botanist to the field of geology. in stark contrast to the good work currently being done by modern thespians in the field of climatology, the work of pallas was proven to be erroneous.

back to the big beautiful crane #bbc the white naped crane, harkening from the far reaches of the #greatwallofchina to mongolia. this crane eats roots and leaves as well as small mammals. once again senseless murder, rabbits have to die because illegal carrot farming operations have drained vast wetlands causing the cranes to impinge upon the farms erstwhile the rabbit population spikes due to the escalating production on efficiency driven farms thus bunny vs crane violent interactions have escalated sinusoidallay in recent years in some part of the cranes range. 
korean natural monument 203 continues to be under dire threat, a scheme sending eggs from the @usa to @china continues to this day, and is possibly the sole cause of the birds extinction in wilderness of the contiguous 48 states. to celebrate the crane and its revered governmental designation, north and south korea set aside a strip of land¬† as habitat for the crane. the #dmz international bird refuge has been an example for the rest of the world since 1953.

#endtheextinction #creaseforpeace #fighttheman #metoo #endtheextinction #earthtoo #cranestoo #lgbqtc @peta @seashepherd #christmas #origami #veget

text:
i do not get involved in any campaign that brings another human being down. after watching the ‚Äúlifetime‚Äù documentary-series called ‚Äúsurviving r. kelly,‚Äù i can no longer support the brand or music of singer robert sylvester kelly aka. r. kelly. i cried as i listened to all of the survivors‚Äô testimonies about their experiences once they moved in with mr. kelly. i cried wondering about the possible experiences that those beautiful children encountered prior to meeting him. my first thought was that we, as a community have failed our children. what could possibly separate a child from their parent? it has to be more than just the fascination of an artist, their music, or the hope for fame. what parent gives a suspected pedophile legal custody of their child? the thought of that breakdown sickens me as well. those who worked in r. kelly‚Äôs camp should also be held accountable as accessories in whatever criminal case arises against him and minors. he could not have done all of this for so long by himself. we are all culpable in the tragedies of these brown babies. we, as a people have spent a lot of time fighting an unjust system that wrongfully seeks to destroy us as a people. we are often the first criminalized, ridiculed, and demonized. as a result, we tend to overcompensate for those amongst us who commit wrongdoings under the pretense of ‚Äúthey‚Äôve been doing it forever.‚Äù wrong is wrong, no matter who the perpetrator is. unfortunately, we have forgiven the perpetrators and forget the casualties and victims of these heinous crimes. as a people, we must have honest dialogue with ourselves about the atrocities of our past. this is bigger than muting r. kelly. we must ask, what have we allowed ourselves to become? from my platform, this will be the last acknowledgement to anything that is affiliated with r. kelly. i was taught a long time ago, a man who won‚Äôt stand for something, will fall for anything. this is my stance. peace!

text:
i don't sleep at night. 
either it's my dreams keeping me awake or my reality keeping me from sleep. 
the reality of realizing that world of peace and humility is a distant fantasy, much like the sleep i often crave. 
dazed and dillusional from an insomniac rush of mania, depressions, work, and oppression of the negative clouds that bring hail when i'm simple looking for rain.

sanity is always near, yet, so is it's kryptonite - consistently hoping that every one after will be a good night. 
the sight of so many people ostracizing and destroying their relationships per the ill education of what it's like to have your soul taken without even a single, "sorry to bother you". more like, sorry to rewrite your future before it's in transcription or giving a dose of adulthood without a prescription. although the label states, 'for consenting adults only'. ----------- to be continued

text:
i lay in my bed 
up at the ungodly hours thinking about you
my eyes always tear up when i think of our times alone together
i know that we will never be together 
just thinking about losing you puts fear in my soul
but in those ungodly hours i pray that i forget you
i pray that somehow i forget that you exist 
praying to forget your touch and your love 
i don‚Äôt know what else to do
when i see your messages i try not to get too excited 
in my mind i tell myself to calm down but my heart jumps for joy that you acknowledge my existence 
i‚Äôm trying to stay away
i wonder if you feel the same way about me
my heart has been really mean to me it throbs and beats fast when i hear your voice or when i see you walk down the hallway 
i stay away because i‚Äôm afraid that you‚Äôll catch on 
my anxiety tells me truthful lies
i suffer in silence to protect myself from being hurt by the one person i truly love 
you
-denise‚õà *my picture and poem*

text:
dear robert "r kelly" kelly, 
i hope this finds you well and in the spirit of the new year!! i'm sure your vexed at this time and feeling the way you feel. as a black girl to black boy im sure you suffered deeply. if i could i would have slashed that man for hurting you. your pain has given you many things and along with that you have become that man in the same way. do the right thing put your money into centers and resources for victims of all situations regarding the allegations alleged in #survivingrkelly. help sick men and woman such as yourself to receive counseling and resources.  i'm so angry at what those predators did to you. i want to ask and assume many things about you and who you really are however, i'm not perfect so who am i but a black girl to a black boy. help us to break the devil i believe we could do it together man. 
a fan of your music.

text: just finished watching #survingrkelly. i have a lot to say. first off, if you‚Äôre an avid r. kelly fan you‚Äôre f***ing gross! that‚Äôs enough about him. i want to shed light of the survivors. the women that worked diligently to bring him to justice. however, they did not fail. the judicial system failed them. why? because they were black and brown girls. it may seem forward of me to say such things but it‚Äôs true. the moment you step into the shoes and life as a woman of color, the world does not come to your rescue. it does not ask if you‚Äôre okay. it does not work in a such a way that makes you equal with others. however, the world is quick to rush to judgement if you fall short on your landing. that is how the cookie has always crumbled. now is the time to say no more! no more to the degradation! no more to the condescending stereotypes! no more to the invisibility! to be honest of sick and tired of being sick and tired of the lack of regard for women of color. women of color are valuable. we are an asset to society. we are contributors to the table. we are people! so treat us as such! if not, hell has no fury like a woman scorned; and she won‚Äôt put her hands on your. she beat you in such a way that you would least imagine: her mind! i‚Äôm a walking testament to that. note to all the black folks: stop being apologetic for disgusting actions! what wrong is wrong! to any survivor that comes across this post: you are loved, you are smart, and you are courageous. no has the right to take your freewill and power to live. so do not let others take that away from. if you come across days where you don‚Äôt have the strength to love yourself, then millions of men and women, including myself, will send our love to you. you are ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è! #stoptheviolence #nomoreabuse #muterkelly #blackgirlslivesmatter #metoo #timesup

acusan de pederastia al cantante @rkelly en un documental.  en el documental surviving r. kelly lucha por denunciar y poner a fin a las dos d√©cadas de supuestos abusos sexuales a menores negras por parte del artista. las women of color (mujeres de color) de la plataforma time‚Äôs up se√±alaban entonces la necesidad de compromiso por parte de grandes empresas de la m√∫sica como rca records, spotify, apple music o ticketmaster -spotify lo sac√≥ de sus listas recopilatorias-. ahora, el esfuerzo por recordar acusaciones como las que irrumpieron primero en el a√±o 2000 en el¬†chicago sun times, donde se recog√≠a que kelly hab√≠a hecho ‚Äúuso de su posici√≥n de fama e influencia como estrella del pop para conocer a chicas de tan solo 15 a√±os y tener relaciones sexuales con ellas‚Äù, se materializa en la producci√≥n de una serie documental en seis partes,¬†surviving r. kelly (lifetime).¬†el esc√°ndalo de su matrimonio por la¬†sex tape¬†en el que se ve√≠a c√≥mo r. kelly manten√≠a relaciones sexuales con una menor de 13 a√±os y orinaba sobre ella, sus otros 21 cargos por pornograf√≠a infantil, y las hasta cuatro demandas de mujeres por mala conducta sexual, violaci√≥n, suministro de drogas ilegales a menores y restricci√≥n ilegal en su casa, son algunos de los turbios episodios que se abordan. algunas celebridades han optado por el silencio y rechazado no aparecer en el documental.

text:
i'm so glad that tonight ended the six episode docuseries because i'm both emotionally drained and spiritually disturbed. i fully expected men to trash the survivors but i was shocked when black women insulted and made fun of the victims in their support of r. kelly. and then they wonder why we continue to say that this world doesn't care about black girls and black women. some of the comments triggered me so bad that i almost raged out. 
some of us are so conditioned to protect the black man at all costs that we can't see the monster right in front of our eyes. we will carry secrets of abuse and more on our back because we are at fault for their actions but that mentality needs to stop. right now.
how many out of court settlements will it take? how many ndas will have to be signed? how many police reports have been filed? how could one disgustingly sick video of a grown man raping a child not send r. kelly to prison for life? how? 
but his music is great, right? the king of r&b, you say.
there's no separation of his professional life and his personal life as his art pays for his demented desires. that is a fact. without your money, r. kelly would not be able to pay his crimes away.
if you can't see all this or acknowledge that this is injustice then you are definitely part of the problem. 
ain't no music that great in the world that would allow me to support a known pedophile and sexual predator. 
we must, as a community, do better.
#survivingrkelly #muterkelly #metoo #timesup

text:
watching #survivingrkelly on #lifetime has triggered so many bad memories. i was taken advantage by two "friends of the family" from ages 9 or 10 until i was like 16. years later, i'm still traumatized by it. #therapy has convinced my head that it wasn't my fault but in my heart i still blame myself. i still feel i should've been smarter. 
while i'm trying to reconcile all of that the biggest thing causing my guilt now is my silence. i never told anyone about it then. i don't really talk about it that much now. i feel that my silence ruined other people's lives. 
i feel that my silence left my nieces and nephews vulnerable to be taken advantage of as well. my silence is unforgivable but i am very sorry.. i'm so sorry that my pain caused me not to be there for you and not warn you and not protect you. i hope #god will forgive me for that. 
from now on, i plan to speak out about what happened to me in the hope that others won't have to fall prey to the many predators that lurk around in plain sight. #nomoresecrets #metoo #muterkelly

text:
on october 22nd, 2018, lauren mccluskey, a 21-year-old university of¬†utah¬†student, was on the phone with her parents when she was attacked. her parents called campus police and 911, overhearing her screams, but it was too late. lauren's ex boyfriend, 37-year old melvin rowland, shot her in the head and killed her. police pursued him, and he ultimately committed suicide during the chase.

but lauren's death was preventable. lauren called the police 6 times in the 10 days before her murder with an increasing level of distress and fear for her life. the campus police at university of utah and the local pd failed to protect lauren, telling her repeatedly that the text messages did not rise to the level of harassment and that the investigation would take time.

lauren was¬†found dead in the back seat of a parked car¬†that same night after rowland, whom she‚Äôd dated for about a month and lied to her about his name, age and criminal background. rowland was¬†convicted of attempted forcible sex abuse¬†and enticing a minor over the internet in 2004. lauren is a part of a growing epidemic of women who are murdered by an intimate partner following ending the relationship.

the university report cites ‚Äúshortcomings‚Äù in the system, such as ‚Äúgaps in training, awareness, and enforcement of certain policies rather than lapses in individual performance‚Äù when describing how campus police handled mccluskey‚Äôs case.
still, university officials said in the report they don‚Äôt believe they could have stopped rowland from murdering mccluskey. campus police failing to check his parole status after finding out about his criminal background is not a "shortcoming," that is one of the many failures that cost lauren her life.
