text:
77/100 ::leap:: the spring of 2016 was the first time i felt a whisper of healing in my body‚Äîa foreign dappled sunlight on my soul‚Äîit left me overwhelmed and squinting in newfound visibility. a fresh layer of dissociation fallen, i felt the hyperreal sting of awakening.
.
this certain moment here held a lifetime of importance‚Äîsun shining in on a warm spring day, listening to this song, spinning my baby in my arms as he smiles with delight, those little sounds he made‚Äîin this feeling, in this moment something gave way that is hard to explain. i began to step into my life. my baby saying ‚Äúmama‚Äù proved i was really here and loved. i was connected to my life and disappearing was no longer an option. in fact my life held joy worth staying for.
.
here i hadn‚Äôt yet uncovered all my memory of abuse or even begun to understand the depth of my dissociation, but the hope in this room let me know i would make it through all i would have to allow myself to feel‚Äîso i could emerge. this little being here took my hand and called me onward, and for him i agreed to keep going no matter how hard. how very far we have come. in this video i could never have dreamed of where i‚Äôd be now, of how much peace i feel in my body.
.
at the dawn of 2019 i have experienced enough to know my future holds more magic and love then i can fathom. 2019 is a leap, i have leapt many times before but now i know i land so the difference is‚Äîtoday i can extend my arms, take flight, and smile, even when my belly flips with that old familiar anxiety. .
i have looked deep into my shadow and stared those demons down, until they arose my allies, my witness, and my strength. my darkness walks with me, on my side.
.
2019 is a still soundless space of mystery beneath my feet and i step forward with my heart open, ready to catch what awaits. this mysterious new space asks me to step off the treadmill of trauma with all it‚Äôs static‚Äîand learn how to enjoy and celebrate my life for real, it is time. today, i stand deeply rooted in memories like these that have shaped my heart, and i look forward.

text:
if time heals all, then how much time will it take? why has it been taking so long. and why every time we think we are done healing, that we are ready to move on, we are shown how wrong we are. we find out what we thought we were dealing with we actually weren't. 
i've been through a lot in my life i shouldn't have survived but somehow i did. i usually attribute it to my books and my writing... because there have been days that stretched into years where writing and stories were the only reasons to keep going. 
writing, telling stories, capturing moments of beauty, the good and the bad... this is what has and always will drive me. 
lately though, things have been spinning, because i've been trying  hard to ignore certain losses. certain things that i hadn't accepted and things i couldn't imagine not coming back...but i thought i had healed. i thought i'd felt all the bad. gone through counseling. and i was healed. even though every *good* counselor i've seen has told me healing isn't linear. 
tonight...i was reminded of that. 
there's so much i have to heal in my life. so much more i have to grow. my family too.  healing isn't linear. more importantly, as much as i want it to be as simple as a checklist, it isn't. 
this fact alone remains.  sometimes i'm not sure if anyone ever heals because the act of healing is so counterintuitive. it demands to be felt and heard and held. to heal one must accept and to accept we must embrace the pain exactly as it is and love it. hold it. accept it wholly and completely. give ourselves over to it. our bodies need air like pain needs to be felt.  but, who wants to embrace pain. who wants to face what happened over and over again, any living creature wants to avoid what hurts. it's a biological imperative. 
healing like everything else takes time. it isn't linear. you can accept something and then two days later swing back into denial. healing is a #journey not a race.

text:
a lot of parents don't want to talk about this, but the fact still remains that 63% of all sexual assaults are committed by someone the victim knew.  a client of mine was molested by her older cousin who was suppose to be babysitting them.  she was 7 he was 12. 
how many others share this story. parents be vigilant, know the signs, watch your child's behavior pattern especially when they're around people.

try some of these questions privately: *did you have a good time?
*how did you spend your time?
*what was fun?
*was anything not fun?
*is there anything else you want to tell me?

never think it can't happen to your child

#protectourbabies #selfdefense #glamazonindefense #knowledgeispower #metoo #children #sexualassault #rape #nomeansno #abuse #dmv

when i can was a little girl, my favorite color changed so frequently that my parents stopped paying attention when i would declare ‚Äúmommy, i decided my favorite color isn‚Äôt ___ anymore, it‚Äôs ___.‚Äù i didn‚Äôt understand how with a world filled with so many beautiful colors, i could pick just one favorite...and my parents made me feel like my process was wrong.
üåª
fast forward a decade or so and just a month before the first anniversary of my rape, my dad said ‚Äúi have some doubts‚Äù and my mom just said ‚Äúno‚Äù when i asked if they believed me. i didn‚Äôt ask more questions, i simultaneously couldn‚Äôt and didn‚Äôt need to.
üåª
therapists and friends have wondered aloud ‚Äúhow could they reject you like that?!‚Äù my best guess is that my coping process was ‚Äúwrong‚Äù in their eyes... i didn‚Äôt cry when i told them...i hadn‚Äôt reported it to the police...i hadn‚Äôt gotten medical care.
üåª
the little girl who couldn‚Äôt pick a favorite color the right way also couldn‚Äôt respond the right way to being raped.
üåª
while i don‚Äôt know for certain if that‚Äôs the reason my parents have chosen to reject my truth, i do know it‚Äôs victim blaming in its purest form. there is no ‚Äúright way‚Äù to react when being raped or when telling people or when healing.

text: how i feel about rain on a saturday. . . get it together, san francisco! üòÜüôÑ‚òîÔ∏èüåÅ just one short year ago, looking at a photo from my wedding day would‚Äôve still caused me pain. not the full waves of pain i experienced for much of 2016-2017, but the stinging sensations just beneath your sternum that last for only a few seconds before fading, like embers dying in a fire. anyone else ever experience that? just me? üî•üî•üî• i am proud to say that, today, i can look at this picture & see the girl sarcastically grinning back at me & simply smile. this 23-year-old baby human had absolutely no idea what was in store for her just 3 short years from this day, but i am proud to say she would weather the storms & arrive safely at her dream destination on the other side with the help of her captain & crew. ‚ö°Ô∏è‚õà‚ö°Ô∏èüåäüö¢üïä as i prepare to continue sharing my story with you, i want to make it clear that what i‚Äôm building, a community that engages & supports those affected by trauma, ultimately has little to do with my own personal struggles & healing. while you may be curious to know what i experienced or if i‚Äôm still in the healing process (spoiler alert: at this point, i have good days & bad days, just like literally every other person on the planet), the goal in my vulnerability is this: to give others permission to share their own stories & struggles through reading mine, to realize that they‚Äôre not alone in processing the tough times of life, & to observe examples of others who have made intentional choices to live well despite deep wounds that could‚Äôve influenced a very different outcome. üôèüíõ can you do something for me? would you tag someone below who could benefit from a community such as this, even simply as an observer? üë´üë≠üë¨ maybe the person who could benefit most is you. if that‚Äôs the case, i pray that you grow from your trauma to someday share your own story & help others along in the process. krysta xo

bette midler renewed an allegation of 1970s sexual misconduct against geraldo rivera on thursday, a day after rivera called the news business ‚Äúflirty‚Äù amid matt lauer‚Äôs dismissal by nbc.

in the tweet posted by the actor-singer and confirmed by her publicist, she included a video from the 1991 interview with barbara walters in which midler made the allegation against rivera. ‚Äútomorrow is my birthday. i feel like this video was a gift from the universe to me. geraldo may have apologized for his tweets supporting matt lauer, but he has yet to apologize for this,‚Äù midler posted, adding the harassment-solidarity hashtag ‚Äú#metoo‚Äù. a representative for rivera did not immediately respond to a request for comment. fox news channel, which currently employs rivera but did not in the 70s, did not immediately comment on midler‚Äôs post.

in the clip, midler hesitates in recounting what she alleges happened with rivera during his visit to interview her in the early 70s, saying it will get her in trouble. ‚Äúget in a little trouble,‚Äù walters encourages her.

after rivera and a producer left their tv crew in another room, they ‚Äúpushed me into my bathroom. they broke two poppers and pushed them under my nose and proceeded to grope me,‚Äù she said. ‚Äúpoppers‚Äù is slang for the alkyl nitrites class of drugs. ‚Äúi did not offer myself up on the altar of geraldo rivera,‚Äù said midler, calling his behavior ‚Äúunseemly‚Äù. after midler tells walters that she had no way of knowing ‚Äúthese things are going to come back to haunt you‚Äù, walters suggests they discuss other subjects.

text: my brother is awesome. we spoke recently about many random jams. dreams, future, locations, lots of stuff. we're both awesomely annoyingly studious. not saying its a defense mechanism or anything, but talking to either of us can be excruciatingly difficult. i used to distract people with the light bulb theory, til oh shit, recognising it was actually the light bulbs, he has his own. new question purposes to explore. we both deal with things that happened differently and love eachother, just depends on where our heads are at, sometimes to best closest conversations, other times, either one of us definetly on pluto. i expressed i might just kinda feel like taking a class or two, maybe not in a serious degree way, just to keep learning and expanding. also with that, another reason to be welcoming to people at the border and all around, those curious adventurers are making way, and we should be proud that they want part in what's happening, and share. then to any high school student and staff, we discussed how i'm not stepping into a class room, so much noise, but some people learn that way. if i take a class it'd be affordable and online, on a weird subject of soo many options. although it brought up the topic of how many schools in this country are predatory and give credits, sure, not ones that are applicable to the work force. i'm not too serious, not certain about a degree, but potentially a class. it is very unaffordable to go to school in this country, and if the affordable schools don't get you hired, well, that's lame. maybe that should be a job, an office job, at all high schools, to search and destroy and out the predatory colleges eating off of people already working towards a come up in the low income life, sharing the insight throughout the districts of hey yeah they'll teach you and give you credits, yet at the same time are not focused to help you progress professionally after you leave. #freepress #metoo text:
the last 90 days have been the hardest of my life.  talking, walking and re-living through shit that i‚Äôve stuffed down since i was 15 is harder than the experience itself.
.
i wish i could say that i‚Äôm happy. .
i‚Äôm happy that i get to have a chance. .
i‚Äôm grateful and excited for my future.  i‚Äôm driven. but my head is in a darker place than i care to admit. the pain is unbearable sometimes....and then i beat it... and then i keep moving forward. .
the pink cloud is not anywhere this time; it‚Äôs black as hell. .
if you‚Äôre struggling just know you‚Äôre not alone.  if i‚Äôve learned anything it‚Äôs that eventually you are going to feel the pain, so why wait for it to get stronger? feel the ache as it as it comes. .
i‚Äôm trying to be grateful that i can feel and that my life is worth feeling this shit instead of numbing it out while killing my life along the way. .
just remember you are worth it and bug the shit out of people who can help you.  don‚Äôt be scared to reach out, it‚Äôs literally the only reason i‚Äôve made it this far. .
happy 90 to me.#retread .

text:
how men got falsely accused of sexual assault. after the office of civil rights (ocr) released their ‚Äúdear colleagues‚Äù letter in 2011, swaths of men were assumed to be guilty of sexual misconduct every time an accusation was made.

this is because schools were required by law to follow the lowest standard of evidence, termed a ‚Äúpreponderance of the evidence.‚Äù men who were accused were assumed to be guilty.

the reason this lower standard of evidence was used is because other civil rights complaints follow this standard. however, civil rights complaints also involve cross-examination and other procedures which ensure the rights of the accused. the ocr threw those procedures out in their handling of sexual assault. why? ask obama.

200 lawsuits later, betsy devos, scotus, amended title ix to ensure the rights of the accused. thank you @betsydevosed for making america and society great again.

this image comes from the vengallatore vs cornell university lawsuit which will be discussed further on the @yogioabs youtube channel shortly.

text:
i typically enter each new year feeling a bit nostalgic, choosing to look back at the holiday season versus looking forward to the new year. but something has shifted this time around..
‚Ä¢
i enter 2019 feeling more confident in myself than i ever have before. i understand who i am, i‚Äôm proud of the person i‚Äôve become and i can finally see beauty in my reflection. with the help of dear friends, i was able to share and process some long-held secrets that impacted my perception of myself in very negative ways. i was able to let go of guilt and harness strength. i understand my reactions to stressors, fears and change. i‚Äôm able to better adapt because of this awareness. i also feel humbled by my body. while i still struggle to accept myself fully, i have made great strides in my battle with #bodydysmorphia and respect what my body is still capable of doing at my age. i‚Äôm able to command it to do things‚Äî to use what i‚Äôve been given to push myself to new limits, to move past physical and mental barriers, to see past doubts and i‚Äôm also still able to love.
‚Ä¢
am i perfect? goodness no. do i make mistakes and fail to live up to others‚Äô expectations of me? yes. do i accept that this is ok? finally, yes. am i angry that it took me 31 years to get here? you‚Äôre damn right! but i‚Äôm more thankful [than angry] to have finally arrived here. i see a realm of possibility in 2019 and foster this new found strength from here. i see my dreams and i‚Äôm more focused on achieving them than ever before.
‚Ä¢
so here‚Äôs to another 365 days around the sun. let us honor the light, beauty, vulnerability and strength within ourselves and others. let us choose love and let us be open to new possibilities for what this life can hold for us. #2019 #selflove #liveyourtruestself #focused #free #liveyouryoga #powerofshe #strongher #metoo #thefutureisfemale #iowa365 #coimcominforyou

text: this is what another concussion does after you've already had numerous concussions including ones with the loss of consciousness. i ended up fighting my brother. he needed an mri because i had "retard rage" for lack of a better term. i wasn't charged for the but this recent concussion in 2010 sent me from having left the air force with a letter of recommendation to first cutting up power cords in my house cuz i thought electronics were alive and trying to get me to hitting my mom and being charged with domestic abuse. i live with my mom per her request. the state or whatever wanted to put me in a home or something. she's my payee for my disability check currently. but the first time in jail was for cutting cords and one was the 220 volt freezer cord. it was thick and took several tries and knocked me back each time and left gouges in the metal part of the scissors. i was sent to jail rather than a hospital unfortunately. that and the toxic food and just not recovering from the brain damage led me to going off to vegas in my car where i was slipped drugs, ended up losing my car, and becoming homeless in portland. i got real sick, they did a spinal tap in the er there, gave me zithromax and some other antibiotics for god knows what. i can't remember. i ended up in ogden after catching pneumonia anyway in i'm portland in spite of meds and spent 5 days in mckay-dee hospital. i was homeless in ogden a bit then slc. i slept outside in a snow storm a couple of times in my shorts and a parka week my knees in my chest. in slc i got more concussions, food poisoning that had me in the er overnight with an iv. i had broken ribs i didn't get treated for a month or more i finally got x rays and they said i had chest wall contusions. i got slipped drugs there too. i got threatened by a guy i heard was associated with a latin gang that tried to force me to join in the 90s and followed me for years. he admitted to being in jail for drugs but claimed he was inocente but the latinos i hung out with told me he asked them for mota. i ended up pissing him off and getting threats from him and his friends. he warned me to just take my meds and go home before that. i ate a lot of bad

text:
2018 celebrated the centenary of women winning the right to vote. there were statues, plaques, films, documentaries, marches and all sorts of things happening to commemorate this important event.
i hope that in 2019 and every year going forward that we continue to remember the suffarge movement - celebrating the achievements that were made, and the sacrifices. we must continue the fight, whether it's been 100 years or 500 years, we must never forget. 
pic of the emily davison plaque that hangs in a broom cupboard in the house of commons, put there by tony benn and jeremy corbyn in 1991.

text:
heading out to miami later tonight for youngarts week. pretty excited but also kinda nervous. this one‚Äôs called ‚Äúman up.‚Äù it‚Äôs one of the images i included in my portfolio for youngarts. i remember hearing about this spontaneous demonstration during break while i was up in the photo room and scrambling to grab a camera. this demonstration took place after brett kavanaugh‚Äôs hearing. it started out with just this one teacher, mr. facione, walking around the campus with that sign. by the end of the 20 minute break there was about 100 people that had joined him. every year our school holds a justice summit which is a yearlong event that tackles a prevalent social issue in today‚Äôs world. this year‚Äôs theme is ‚Äúgender.‚Äù one thing i‚Äôve come to learn is that we all contribute in some manner to gender stereotypes. and i think that these stereotypes limit us. along with that there are a lot of conventions in place within our society that are ‚Äúacceptable.‚Äù unfortunately, it seems like sexual assault is one of those things. it‚Äôs one of those things that‚Äôs been going on for so long but because of the power structures in place and the stigma of sexual assault for victims nobody wants to talk about it and because of that nothing changes. one of the most difficult things to do is acknowledge your flaws. however, i believe that if we start to do that with these uncomfortable issues we can begin to make change.

text:
darryl smith came to visit us at the hope centre on friday. darryl was abused by members of the catholic church while enduring more than a decade of torment in state care in new zealand and australia, beginning in the late 1970s. 
darryl is away to to visit the vatican in february to take to task for what happened to him and thousands of others. he hopes to meet pope francis. 
darryl will be wearing the life matters cap on his travels and hope to get a photo taken in rome with the pope. 
confronting those who are in positions of power is never easy so we wish him well. 
#youarethechange
